Let’s take a look how observations are distributed across different features with respect to a class label. For this, we plot a scatterplot matrix:

featurePlot(x=df[,-5], y=df[,5], plot="ellipse")

Classification

To estimate the misclassification error, we use 10-fold cross-validation.

control <- trainControl(method="cv", number=10)
metric <- "Accuracy"

We train two classifiers: LDA and kNN. For the latter one, we try out number of neighbours between 1 and 25.

fit.lda <- train(Species~., data=df, method="lda", metric=metric, trControl=control)

fit.knn <- train(Species~., data=df, method="knn", metric=metric, trControl=control, tuneGrid = expand.grid(k = 1:25))

Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Data Set

In this section classification of diagnostic of breast cancer is studied. It is required to predict whether the analysis result is malignant or benign. The data set can be extracted from the UCI repository as follows:

breast <- read.table(url("http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/breast-cancer-wisconsin/breast-cancer-wisconsin.data"), sep = ',', na.strings = "?")

A feature that identifies an id number of a patient was removed from the data. In addition, Bare Nuclei has missing values. We subsititute NA by the average value.

# delete id
breast <- breast[,-1]
# y is converted s.t. labels are -1 and 1
y <- ifelse(breast$V11=='2', 1, -1)
X <- breast[,-10]
# check all columns for NA
j<-which(sapply(1:ncol(X), function(i) all(!is.na(X[,i])))==F)
# substitute NA by mean values
X[is.na(X[,j]),j] <- mean(X[,j], na.rm = T)

Instead of the cross-validation, we use train/test split in this section. The proportions are 60%/40%.

sample <- sample.int(n = nrow(X), size = floor(0.6*nrow(X)), replace = F)
train_x <- X[sample, ]
train_y <- y[sample]
test_x <- X[-sample, ]
test_y <- y[-sample]

The perceptron algorithm generally works better when all features are rescaled to the same value range (why?). Also, we add a feature to fake the intercept.

# feature rescaling
X <- as.data.frame(apply(X,2,function(x){(x-mean(x))/sd(x)}))
# adding intercept
X$intercept <- 1
# train and test for perceptron
train_x_c <- X[sample, ]
test_x_c <- X[-sample, ]

We consider the following classifiers: kNN with 1,4,10 neighbours, LDA and perceptron.

# knn-1
pred <- knn(train_x, test_x, train_y, k = 1)

# knn-4
pred <- knn(train_x, test_x, train_y, k = 4)

# knn-10
pred <- knn(train_x, test_x, train_y, k = 10)

# lda
fit <- lda(train_x, train_y)
pred <- predict(fit, test_x)$class

# perceptron
fit <- perceptrain(train_x_c, train_y, alpha_k = 0.05, endcost = 10000)
w<-c(fit$z[-1],fit$z[1])
pred<-sign(as.matrix(test_x_c) %*% w)

# naive Bayes
fit <- naive_bayes(train_x, train_y)
pred <- predict(fit, test_x)

Handwritten Digits Data

We consider the database of hadnwritten digits. In this case, one observation is an image that is stored as an array of pixel intensities. For sake of simiplicity, let’s keep three classes that corresponds to digits 1,2,3.

# read data
zippict<-zip.train
bool<-(zippict[,1]==1 |zippict[,1]==2) | zippict[,1]==3
zipaux<-zippict[bool,]

# dimension of the data
n<-dim(zipaux)[1]
p<-dim(zipaux)[2]

# display 9 images
par(mfrow=c(3,3),mar=c(2, 2, 4, 2)+0.1)
for (i in 10+(1:9)){mm<-(matrix(as.numeric((zipaux[i,2:257])),nrow=16,byrow=F))
image(z=mm[,16:1],col=grey((0:256)/256),xaxt="n",yaxt="n")}

zipaux<-data.frame(cbind(as.factor(zipaux[,1]),zipaux[,-1]))
library(caTools)
train_ind <- sample.split(zipaux[,1], SplitRatio = 0.7)

library(caret)
bad_ind <- checkConditionalX(zipaux[,-1], y=zipaux[,1])
bad_ind <- bad_ind + 1
zip_df <- zipaux[,-bad_ind]
train_set <- zip_df[train_ind,]
test_set <- zip_df[-train_ind,]
fit <- lda(train_set[,-1], train_set[,1])
pred_test <- predict(fit, test_set[,-1])$class
print("Accuracy:")
## [1] "Accuracy:"
print(sum(pred_test==test_set[,1])/(nrow(test_set)))
## [1] 0.9933138
